#SSH Time evolution


import numpy as np 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.linalg import expm
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D  # 3D plotting toolkit

def build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma):
    """
    Build the SSH Hamiltonian on a 1D lattice of N sites.
    """
    H = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N-1):
        # Scale the hopping amplitudes with position
        v_i = v * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        w_i = w * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        if i % 2 == 0:
            H[i, i+1] = -v_i
            H[i+1, i] = -v_i
        else:
            H[i, i+1] = -w_i
            H[i+1, i] = -w_i
    return H

def tb_model(N, sigma):
    """
    Build a tight-binding model Hamiltonian for comparison.
    """
    J = 1
    H_tb = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N - 1):
        J_i = J * ((i + 1) / (N - 1))**sigma
        H_tb[i, i + 1] = -J_i
        H_tb[i + 1, i] = -J_i
    return H_tb

def kitaev_chain(N, mu, t, delta, sigma):
    # Construct the N x N matrices A (kinetic part) and B (pairing part)
    A = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    B = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)

    for i in range(N):
        A[i, i] = -mu  # on-site energy
        if i < N - 1:
            t_i = -t * ((i + 1) / (N - 1))**sigma
            A[i, i+1] = -t_i
            A[i+1, i] = -t_i
            B[i, i+1] = delta
            B[i+1, i] = -delta

    H_kc = np.block([
        [A,         B],
        [B.conj().T, -A.conj().T]
    ])
    return H_kc

def boosted_dirac_delta(N, n0, p0):
    psi = np.zeros(N, dtype=complex)
    n0_int = int(n0)
    psi[n0_int] = np.exp(1j * p0 * n0_int)
    return psi

def gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega):
    """
    Create a Gaussian wave packet.
    """
    n = np.arange(N)
    psi = np.exp(-0.5 * ((n - n0) / omega)**2) * np.exp(1j * p0 * n)
    psi /= np.linalg.norm(psi)
    return psi

def run_time_evolution(N, v, w, sigma, mu, t, delta, n0, p0, omega, dt, T, plot_times):
    """
    Evolve an initial wave packet under the SSH Hamiltonian.
    """
    # 1) Build the Hamiltonians
    H_SSH = build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma)
    H_tb = tb_model(N, sigma)
    H_kitaev = kitaev_chain(N, mu, t, delta, sigma)
    
    # 2) Build the time evolution operator U = exp(-i H dt)
    U = expm(-1j * H_SSH * dt)
    
    # 3) Create the initial wavefunction (using a Gaussian)
    psi = gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega)
    
    # 4) Determine the number of time steps and record the initial state
    t_steps = int(np.round(T / dt))
    psi_t = [np.abs(psi.copy())]
    
    # 5) Evolve the wavefunction in time
    for step in range(t_steps):
        psi = U @ psi
        psi_t.append(np.abs(psi))
    
    # 6) (Optional) Original 3D plot of the full evolution snapshots
    times_to_plot = np.linspace(0, t_steps, plot_times, dtype=int)
    positions = np.arange(N)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 9))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
    
    for t_idx in times_to_plot:
        time_val = t_idx * dt
        y_vals = np.full(positions.shape, time_val)
        z_vals = psi_t[t_idx]
        ax.plot(positions, y_vals, z_vals, label=f"t = {time_val:.1f}")
    
    ax.set_xlabel("Site index n")
    ax.set_ylabel("Time t")
    ax.set_zlabel(r"$|\psi(n,t)|$")
    ax.set_title(f"3D Time Evolution of Gaussian Packet\n(SSH Hamiltonian: v={v}, w={w}, ={sigma}, $p_0$={p0}) \n(formula turning point={n0/1000*((np.cos(p0))**(2/sigma)+((w/v-1)/(w/v+1))**(2/sigma))**0.5})")
    plt.show()
    
   
#####################################################################################################

    # 7) Compute the peak positions and rescaled values for the 2D plot.
    peak_positions = []
    rescaled_times = []
    rescaled_positions = []
    for step, psi_abs in enumerate(psi_t):
        peak_index = np.argmax(psi_abs)  # peak position at this time step
        peak_positions.append(peak_index)
        t_val = step * dt
        rescaled_times.append(t_val / N)         # t = t/N
        rescaled_positions.append(peak_index / N)  # x = x/N

    # Determine the turning point (the minimum of the rescaled positions)
    turning_index = np.argmin(rescaled_positions)
    turning_time = rescaled_times[turning_index]
    turning_pos = rescaled_positions[turning_index]

    # 8) Create a 2D plot of rescaled peak position vs. rescaled time.
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(rescaled_positions, rescaled_times, 'o-', color='blue', markersize=1, label="Peak trajectory")
    # Mark the turning point with a red star
    plt.plot(turning_pos, turning_time, 'r*', markersize=12, label="Turning point")
    plt.xlabel(r"Rescaled peak position $\tilde{x} = x/N$")
    plt.ylabel(r"Rescaled time $\tilde{t} = t/N$")
    plt.title(f"2D Plot of Rescaled Time vs. Peak Position of Gaussian Wavepacket($p_0$={p0}),\n(formula turning point={n0/N*((np.cos(p0))**(2/sigma)+((w/v-1)/(w/v+1))**(2/sigma))**0.5})")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    
    # Optionally add an annotation for clarity
    plt.annotate(f"Turning Point\n($x_{{min}}$={turning_pos:.3f}, $t$={turning_time:.3f})", 
                 xy=(turning_pos, turning_time), 
                 xytext=(turning_pos+0.05, turning_time+0.05),
                 arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', arrowstyle='->'))
    
    plt.show()
###########################################################################################################################################
if __name__ == "__main__":

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.linalg import expm

###############################################################################
#                           SSH TIME EVOLUTION CODE                           #
###############################################################################
def build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma):
    """
    Build the SSH Hamiltonian on a 1D lattice of N sites.
    """
    H = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N-1):
        v_i = v * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        w_i = w * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        if i % 2 == 0:
            H[i, i+1] = -v_i
            H[i+1, i] = -v_i
        else:
            H[i, i+1] = -w_i
            H[i+1, i] = -w_i
    return H

def gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega):
    """
    Create a Gaussian wave packet.
    """
    n = np.arange(N)
    psi = np.exp(-0.5 * ((n - n0) / omega)**2) * np.exp(1j * p0 * n)
    psi /= np.linalg.norm(psi)
    return psi

def simulate_turning_point(w, N, v, sigma, n0, p0, omega, dt, T):
    """
    Run the SSH time evolution for the given parameters.
    
    Modified logic:
      - Record the rescaled peak positions (x) vs time.
      - Ignore the first few time steps (to skip initial fluctuations).
      - Find the first index j (after the ignored period) at which the peak position
        reaches a local maximum (i.e. the peak reverses and starts to go downward).
      - In the time interval from t = 0 up to that index j, choose the minimum peak 
        position as the turning point.
    
    Returns:
      turning_time, turning_pos.
    """
    # Build SSH Hamiltonian and time-evolution operator.
    H_SSH = build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma)
    U = expm(-1j * H_SSH * dt)
    
    # Initialize wave packet.
    psi = gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega)
    t_steps = int(np.round(T / dt))
    
    # Record the absolute value (peak) of the wavefunction at each time step.
    psi_t = [np.abs(psi.copy())]
    for step in range(t_steps):
        psi = U @ psi
        psi_t.append(np.abs(psi))
    
    rescaled_positions = []
    rescaled_times = []
    for step, psi_abs in enumerate(psi_t):
        peak_index = np.argmax(psi_abs)
        t_val = step * dt
        rescaled_times.append(t_val / N)         # t = t/N
        rescaled_positions.append(peak_index / N)  # x = x/N

    # Convert lists to arrays.
    pos_arr = np.array(rescaled_positions)
    time_arr = np.array(rescaled_times)
    
    # Ignore the first few time steps to bypass initial fluctuations.
    ignore = 1000
    j = None
    # Starting from index 'ignore', look for the first index where the peak reverses,
    # i.e. the first local maximum (peak starts to decrease afterward).
    for i in range(ignore+1, len(pos_arr)-1):
        # We want to find the first index j such that pos[j-1] < pos[j] and pos[j] > pos[j+1]
        if pos_arr[i] > pos_arr[i-1] and pos_arr[i] > pos_arr[i+1]:
            j = i
            break
    if j is None:
        j = len(pos_arr)
    
    # Now, consider only the time interval from t=0 to t(j) and find the minimum.
    sub_positions = pos_arr[:j]
    turning_index = np.argmin(sub_positions)
    turning_time = time_arr[turning_index]
    turning_pos = sub_positions[turning_index]
    
    return turning_time, turning_pos

###############################################################################
#                  ANALYTICAL TURNING POINT FORMULA                          #
###############################################################################
def analytic_turning_point(N, n0, sigma, v, w, p0):
    """
    Compute the analytical turning point.
    For example, using the formula:
      x_min = (n0/N) * sqrt( cos(p0)^(2/sigma) + ((w/v - 1)/(w/v + 1))^(2/sigma) )
    (This formula is heuristic; adjust as needed.)
    """
    term1 = np.cos(p0)**(2/sigma)
    term2 = ((w/v - 1) / (w/v + 1))**(2/sigma)
    return (n0 / N) * np.sqrt(term1 + term2)

###############################################################################
#                          MAIN COMPARISON CODE                             #
###############################################################################
if __name__ == "__main__":
    # Fixed parameters for SSH simulation
    N = 1000         # number of lattice sites
    v = 1            # hopping parameter v (fixed)
    w = 1.8          # hopping parameter w (fixed)
    sigma = 1.2       # exponent
    n0 = 800         # center of Gaussian (in lattice units)
    omega = 9        # width of Gaussian
    dt = 0.1         # time step
    T = 1000         # total evolution time

    # For the simulation turning point, use a coarse grid of p0 values (e.g. 21 points).
    p0_list_SSH = np.linspace(0, -np.pi/2, 21)

    p0_list = np.linspace(0,-np.pi/2 , 101)
    x_list=p0_list*(-2/np.pi)
    p0_list_SSH= np.linspace(0,-np.pi/2 , 11)
    x_list_SSH=p0_list_SSH*(-2/np.pi)

    sim_turning_points = []
    for p0 in p0_list_SSH:
        _, turning_pos_sim = simulate_turning_point(w, N, v, sigma, n0, p0, omega, dt, T)
        sim_turning_points.append(turning_pos_sim)
    
    # For the analytical formula, use a finer grid (e.g. 101 points)
    p0_list_analytic = np.linspace(0, -np.pi/2, 101)

    p0_list = np.linspace(0,-np.pi/2 , 101)
    x_list=p0_list*(-2/np.pi)
    p0_list_SSH= np.linspace(0,-np.pi/2 , 11)
    x_list_SSH=p0_list_SSH*(-2/np.pi)

    analytic_turning_points = [analytic_turning_point(N, n0, sigma, v, w, p0) for p0 in p0_list_analytic]
    
    # For plotting, we can plot vs p0 (in radians)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(x_list_SSH, sim_turning_points, 'o', markersize=6, label="SSH Simulation (coarse)")
    plt.plot(x_list, analytic_turning_points, '--', markersize=6, label="Analytical Formula (fine)")
    plt.xlabel("Initial momentum $p_0$ (radians)")
    plt.ylabel("Rescaled Turning Point $x_{min}$")
    plt.title("Turning Point vs. Initial Momentum\nfor fixed (v, w) = (1, 1.5), $\sigma$ = 1")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

from scipy.linalg import expm

# Define your helper functions
def build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma):
    H = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N-1):
        v_i = v * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        w_i = w * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        if i % 2 == 0:
            H[i, i+1] = -v_i
            H[i+1, i] = -v_i
        else:
            H[i, i+1] = -w_i
            H[i+1, i] = -w_i
    return H

    n = np.arange(N)

    psi /= np.linalg.norm(psi)
    return psi

def simulate_turning_point(w, N, v, sigma, n0, p0, omega, dt, T):
    """
    Run the time evolution for the SSH Hamiltonian with a given w and return the turning point,
    i.e. the minimum rescaled peak position and its corresponding rescaled time.
    """
    # Build Hamiltonian and time evolution operator (using SSH Hamiltonian)
    H_SSH = build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma)
    U = expm(-1j * H_SSH * dt)
    
    # Initialize wave packet
    psi = gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega)
    t_steps = int(np.round(T / dt))
    
    # Record the absolute value of the wavefunction at each time step
    psi_t = [np.abs(psi.copy())]
    for step in range(t_steps):
        psi = U @ psi
        psi_t.append(np.abs(psi))
    
    # Compute rescaled peak positions and times
    rescaled_positions = []
    rescaled_times = []
    for step, psi_abs in enumerate(psi_t):
        peak_index = np.argmax(psi_abs)
        t_val = step * dt
        rescaled_times.append(t_val / N)         # t = t/N
        rescaled_positions.append(peak_index / N)  # x = x/N
    
    # Determine the turning point (minimum rescaled peak position)
    turning_index = np.argmin(rescaled_positions)
    turning_time = rescaled_times[turning_index]
    turning_pos = rescaled_positions[turning_index]
    
    return turning_time, turning_pos

#INITIAL MOMENTUM VS THE TURNING POINT (NUMERICAL VS THE ANALYRICAL FORULA)

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.linalg import expm

###############################################################################
#                           SSH TIME EVOLUTION CODE                           #
###############################################################################
def build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma):
    H = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N-1):
        v_i = v * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        w_i = w * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        if i % 2 == 0:
            H[i, i+1] = -v_i
            H[i+1, i] = -v_i
        else:
            H[i, i+1] = -w_i
            H[i+1, i] = -w_i
    return H

def gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega):
    n = np.arange(N)
    psi = np.exp(-0.5*((n - n0)/omega)**2) * np.exp(1j*p0*n)
    psi /= np.linalg.norm(psi)
    return psi

def simulate_turning_point(w, N, v, sigma, n0, p0, omega, dt, T):
    """
    Run the time evolution for the SSH Hamiltonian with the given parameters.
    Return the turning point (i.e. the minimum rescaled peak position) and its time.
    """
    H_SSH = build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma)
    U = expm(-1j * H_SSH * dt)
    psi = gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega)
    t_steps = int(np.round(T / dt))
    
    psi_t = [np.abs(psi.copy())]

#SSH Time evolution


import numpy as np 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.linalg import expm
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D  # 3D plotting toolkit

def build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma):
    """
    Build the SSH Hamiltonian on a 1D lattice of N sites.
    """
    H = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N-1):
        # Scale the hopping amplitudes with position
        v_i = v * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        w_i = w * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        if i % 2 == 0:
            H[i, i+1] = -v_i
            H[i+1, i] = -v_i
        else:
            H[i, i+1] = -w_i
            H[i+1, i] = -w_i
    return H

def tb_model(N, sigma):
    """
    Build a tight-binding model Hamiltonian for comparison.
    """
    J = 1
    H_tb = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N - 1):
        J_i = J * ((i + 1) / (N - 1))**sigma
        H_tb[i, i + 1] = -J_i
        H_tb[i + 1, i] = -J_i
    return H_tb

def kitaev_chain(N, mu, t, delta, sigma):
    # Construct the N x N matrices A (kinetic part) and B (pairing part)
    A = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    B = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)

    for i in range(N):
        A[i, i] = -mu  # on-site energy
        if i < N - 1:
            t_i = -t * ((i + 1) / (N - 1))**sigma
            A[i, i+1] = -t_i
            A[i+1, i] = -t_i
            B[i, i+1] = delta
            B[i+1, i] = -delta

    H_kc = np.block([
        [A,         B],
        [B.conj().T, -A.conj().T]
    ])
    return H_kc

def boosted_dirac_delta(N, n0, p0):
    psi = np.zeros(N, dtype=complex)
    n0_int = int(n0)
    psi[n0_int] = np.exp(1j * p0 * n0_int)
    return psi

def gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega):
    """
    Create a Gaussian wave packet.
    """
    n = np.arange(N)
    psi = np.exp(-0.5 * ((n - n0) / omega)**2) * np.exp(1j * p0 * n)
    psi /= np.linalg.norm(psi)
    return psi

def run_time_evolution(N, v, w, sigma, mu, t, delta, n0, p0, omega, dt, T, plot_times):
    """
    Evolve an initial wave packet under the SSH Hamiltonian.
    """
    # 1) Build the Hamiltonians
    H_SSH = build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma)
    H_tb = tb_model(N, sigma)
    H_kitaev = kitaev_chain(N, mu, t, delta, sigma)
    
    # 2) Build the time evolution operator U = exp(-i H dt)
    U = expm(-1j * H_SSH * dt)
    
    # 3) Create the initial wavefunction (using a Gaussian)
    psi = gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega)
    
    # 4) Determine the number of time steps and record the initial state
    t_steps = int(np.round(T / dt))
    psi_t = [np.abs(psi.copy())]
    
    # 5) Evolve the wavefunction in time
    for step in range(t_steps):
        psi = U @ psi
        psi_t.append(np.abs(psi))
    
    # 6) (Optional) Original 3D plot of the full evolution snapshots
    times_to_plot = np.linspace(0, t_steps, plot_times, dtype=int)
    positions = np.arange(N)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 9))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
    
    for t_idx in times_to_plot:
        time_val = t_idx * dt
        y_vals = np.full(positions.shape, time_val)
        z_vals = psi_t[t_idx]
        ax.plot(positions, y_vals, z_vals, label=f"t = {time_val:.1f}")
    
    ax.set_xlabel("Site index n")
    ax.set_ylabel("Time t")
    ax.set_zlabel(r"$|\psi(n,t)|$")
    ax.set_title(f"3D Time Evolution of Gaussian Packet\n(SSH Hamiltonian: v={v}, w={w}, ={sigma}, $p_0$={p0}) \n(formula turning point={n0/1000*((np.cos(p0))**(2)+((w/v-1)/(w/v+1))**(2)-(np.cos(p0))**(2)*((w/v-1)/(w/v+1))**(2))**(1/(2*sigma))})")
    plt.show()
    
   
#####################################################################################################

    # 7) Compute the peak positions and rescaled values for the 2D plot.
    peak_positions = []
    rescaled_times = []
    rescaled_positions = []
    for step, psi_abs in enumerate(psi_t):
        peak_index = np.argmax(psi_abs)  # peak position at this time step
        peak_positions.append(peak_index)
        t_val = step * dt
        rescaled_times.append(t_val / N)         # t = t/N
        rescaled_positions.append(peak_index / N)  # x = x/N

    # Determine the turning point (the minimum of the rescaled positions)
    turning_index = np.argmin(rescaled_positions)
    turning_time = rescaled_times[turning_index]
    turning_pos = rescaled_positions[turning_index]

    # 8) Create a 2D plot of rescaled peak position vs. rescaled time.
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(rescaled_positions, rescaled_times, 'o-', color='blue', markersize=1, label="Peak trajectory")
    # Mark the turning point with a red star
    plt.plot(turning_pos, turning_time, 'r*', markersize=12, label="Turning point")
    plt.xlabel(r"Rescaled peak position $\tilde{x} = x/N$")
    plt.ylabel(r"Rescaled time $\tilde{t} = t/N$")
    plt.title(f"2D Plot of Rescaled Time vs. Peak Position of Gaussian Wavepacket($p_0$={p0}),\n(formula turning point={n0/N*((np.cos(p0))**(2)+((w/v-1)/(w/v+1))**(2)-(np.cos(p0))**(2)*((w/v-1)/(w/v+1))**(2))**(1/(2*sigma))})")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    
    # Optionally add an annotation for clarity
    plt.annotate(f"Turning Point\n($x_{{min}}$={turning_pos:.4f}, $t$={turning_time:.3f})", 
                 xy=(turning_pos, turning_time), 
                 xytext=(turning_pos+0.05, turning_time+0.05),
                 arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', arrowstyle='->'))
    
    plt.show()

      x_min = (n0/N) * sqrt( cos(p0)^(2/sigma) + ((w/v - 1)/(w/v + 1))^(2/sigma) )

#Brut force discrete vs SSH time evolution

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.linalg import expm
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

###############################################################################
#                           1) NUMERICAL CODE (SSH)                           #
###############################################################################
def build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma):
    """
    Build the SSH Hamiltonian on a 1D lattice of N sites.
    """
    H = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N-1):
        # Scale the hopping amplitudes with position
        v_i = v * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        w_i = w * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        if i % 2 == 0:
            H[i, i+1] = -v_i
            H[i+1, i] = -v_i
        else:
            H[i, i+1] = -w_i
            H[i+1, i] = -w_i
    return H

def gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega):
    """
    Create a Gaussian wave packet.
    """
    n = np.arange(N)
    psi = np.exp(-0.5 * ((n - n0) / omega)**2) * np.exp(1j * p0 * n)
    psi /= np.linalg.norm(psi)
    return psi

def run_time_evolution_ssh(N, v, w, sigma, n0, p0, omega, dt, T):
    """
    Evolve an initial Gaussian wave packet under the SSH Hamiltonian
    and return (rescaled_positions, rescaled_times).
    """
    # 1) Build the SSH Hamiltonian
    H_SSH = build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma)

    # 2) Build time-evolution operator
    U = expm(-1j * H_SSH * dt)

    # 3) Create initial wavefunction
    psi = gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega)

    # 4) Time steps
    t_steps = int(np.round(T / dt))
    psi_t = [np.abs(psi.copy())]

    # 5) Evolve wavefunction in time
    for step in range(t_steps):
        psi = U @ psi
        psi_t.append(np.abs(psi))

    # 6) Identify the peak at each step and build rescaled arrays
    peak_positions = []
    rescaled_times = []
    rescaled_positions = []
    for step, psi_abs in enumerate(psi_t):
        peak_index = np.argmax(psi_abs)  # peak position
        peak_positions.append(peak_index)
        t_val = step * dt
        rescaled_times.append(t_val / N)           # t = t / N
        rescaled_positions.append(peak_index / N)  # x = x / N

    return np.array(rescaled_positions), np.array(rescaled_times)

###############################################################################
#                      2) BRUTE-FORCE INTEGRATION CODE                        #
###############################################################################
def compute_integrated_t(x0, x_end, sigma, p0, t1, t2, delta_x=1.0, branch=1):
    """
    Forward integration from x0 down to x_end,
    returning arrays of x_values, t_values, and the constant A.
    """
    x_vals_desc = np.arange(x0, x_end - delta_x, -delta_x)
    n_points = len(x_vals_desc)

    # Compute A using t(x0)=t1*x0^sigma
    t_x0 = t1 * (x0 ** sigma)
    A = - (2 * t_x0 * np.cos(p0))**2

    T_vals_desc = np.zeros(n_points)
    dx = delta_x

    for i in range(n_points - 1):
        if i % 2 == 0:
            t_integrand = t1 * (x_vals_desc[i] ** sigma)
        else:
            t_integrand = t2 * (x_vals_desc[i] ** sigma)

        denom = np.sqrt((2 * t_integrand)**2 + A)
        dt = dx / np.maximum(denom, 1e-12)
        T_vals_desc[i+1] = T_vals_desc[i] + dt

    T_vals_desc *= branch

    # Reverse to get ascending x
    x_values = x_vals_desc[::-1]
    t_values = T_vals_desc[::-1]

    return x_values, t_values, A

def compute_integrated_t_asc(x_start, x_end, sigma, p0, t1, t2, delta_x=1.0, branch=1):
    """
    Integration from x_start to x_end,
    returning arrays of x_values, t_values, and the constant A.
    """
    if x_start == 0:
        eps = delta_x
        x_vals_eff = np.arange(eps, x_end + delta_x, delta_x)
        prepend_zero = True
    else:
        x_vals_eff = np.arange(x_start, x_end + delta_x, delta_x)
        prepend_zero = False

    n_points = len(x_vals_eff)

    t_x0 = t1 * (x_end ** sigma)
    A = - (2 * t_x0 * np.cos(p0))**2

    T_vals = np.zeros(n_points)
    dx = delta_x

    for i in range(n_points - 1):
        if i % 2 == 0:
            t_integrand = t1 * (x_vals_eff[i] ** sigma)
        else:
            t_integrand = t2 * (x_vals_eff[i] ** sigma)
        denom = np.sqrt((2 * t_integrand)**2 + A)
        dt = dx / np.maximum(denom, 1e-12)
        T_vals[i+1] = T_vals[i] + dt

    T_vals *= branch

    if prepend_zero:
        x_values = np.concatenate(([0], x_vals_eff))
        T_vals = np.concatenate(([0], T_vals))
    else:
        x_values = x_vals_eff

    return x_values, T_vals, A

###############################################################################
#                            3) COMBINED EXAMPLE                              #
###############################################################################
def main_combined():
    # ====================== Part A: Run the SSH code ====================== #
    N = 1000        # number of lattice sites
    v = 1

    p0_ssh = -np.pi/2

    ssh_positions, ssh_times = run_time_evolution_ssh(

    x0 = 0.8        # "end" for the brute force integrator

    # The total integrated time at x=0 is t_forward[0], so we can offset the backward data
    T_total = t_forward[0]
    t_backward += T_total

        # ============ Part C: Rescale or overlay the two sets of data ============ #

# numerical vs brute force and discrete vs continuous comparison new

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.linalg import expm
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

###############################################################################
#             COSINE-STEP FUNCTION: transitions between t1*x^, t2*x^       #
###############################################################################
def raised_cosine_step(alpha, w):
    """
    A smooth 0->1 step using a half-cosine window of width w around alpha=0.5.

    - alpha in [0,1)
    - w = 1/freq => small if freq is large => sharper jump
    - if alpha < 0.5-w/2 => step=0
    - if alpha > 0.5+w/2 => step=1
    - else => smooth half-cosine ramp from 0..1
    """
    alpha_arr = np.asarray(alpha, dtype=float)
    step_vals = np.zeros_like(alpha_arr)

    left  = 0.5 - w/2
    right = 0.5 + w/2

    mask0 = (alpha_arr <= left)
    mask1 = (alpha_arr >= right)
    mask_mid = ~(mask0 | mask1)  # in-between region

    # In the middle region => half-cosine from 0..1
    s = (alpha_arr[mask_mid] - left) / (right - left)  # scaled in [0..1]
    step_vals[mask_mid] = 0.5 * (1 - np.cos(np.pi * s))

    step_vals[mask1] = 1.0
    return step_vals

def get_t_integrand_cosstep(x, sigma, t1, t2, freq):
    """
    Continuous function T(x) that, on each integer interval [n, n+1), transitions
    from t1*x^ to t2*x^ (or vice versa) using a raised-cosine step around x=n+0.5.

    At integer n:
      - if n is even => near t1*n^
      - if n is odd  => near t2*n^
    As freq -> large, the step becomes very steep, approximating the
    old discrete pattern (even => t1, odd => t2).
    """
    x_arr = np.asarray(x, dtype=float)
    n = np.floor(x_arr).astype(int)  # integer part
    alpha = x_arr - n                # fractional part in [0..1)
    parity = (n % 2 == 1)            # True if odd, else even

    # base, target
    base = np.where(parity, t2, t1)
    targ = np.where(parity, t1, t2)

    w = 1.0 / freq  # width of the transition zone
    frac = raised_cosine_step(alpha, w)
    amplitude = base + (targ - base)*frac  # blend from base to target

    return x_arr**sigma * amplitude

###############################################################################
#                 DISCRETE INTEGRAND FOR COMPARISON (t1/t2)                   #
###############################################################################
def get_t_integrand_discrete(x, sigma, t1, t2):
    """
    The old piecewise-constant pattern:
      For x in [n, n+1),
        if n is even => t(x)= t1*x^
        if n is odd  => t(x)= t2*x^
    This is 'discrete' in the sense that it flips at each integer x.
    """
    x_arr = np.asarray(x, dtype=float)
    n = np.floor(x_arr).astype(int)
    parity = (n % 2 == 1)  # odd => True
    # even => t1, odd => t2
    base = np.where(parity, t2, t1)
    return (x_arr**sigma)*base

###############################################################################
#                           1) SSH CODE (UNCHANGED)                           #
###############################################################################
def build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma):
    """
    Build the SSH Hamiltonian on a 1D lattice of N sites.
    """
    H = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N-1):
        # Scale hopping with position:
        v_i = v * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        w_i = w * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        if i % 2 == 0:
            H[i, i+1] = -v_i
            H[i+1, i] = -v_i
        else:
            H[i, i+1] = -w_i
            H[i+1, i] = -w_i
    return H

def gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega):
    """
    Create a Gaussian wave packet.
    """
    n = np.arange(N)
    psi = np.exp(-0.5*((n - n0)/omega)**2) * np.exp(1j*p0*n)
    psi /= np.linalg.norm(psi)
    return psi

def run_time_evolution_ssh(N, v, w, sigma, n0, p0, omega, dt, T):
    """
    Evolve an initial Gaussian wave packet under the SSH Hamiltonian
    and return (rescaled_positions, rescaled_times).
    """
    # 1) Build SSH Hamiltonian
    H_SSH = build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma)
    # 2) Time-evolution operator
    U = expm(-1j*H_SSH*dt)
    # 3) Initial wavefunction
    psi = gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega)
    # 4) Number of steps
    t_steps = int(np.round(T / dt))
    psi_t = [np.abs(psi.copy())]

    # 5) Evolve in time
    for step in range(t_steps):
        psi = U @ psi
        psi_t.append(np.abs(psi))

    # 6) Find peak each step => build rescaled arrays
    peak_positions = []
    rescaled_times = []
    rescaled_positions = []
    for step, psi_abs in enumerate(psi_t):
        peak_index = np.argmax(psi_abs)
        peak_positions.append(peak_index)
        t_val = step*dt
        rescaled_times.append(t_val/N)
        rescaled_positions.append(peak_index/N)

    return np.array(rescaled_positions), np.array(rescaled_times)


###############################################################################
#                      2) BRUTE-FORCE INTEGRATION CODE                        #
###############################################################################
def compute_integrated_t(x0, x_end, sigma, p0, t1, t2, freq=1.0, delta_x=1.0, branch=1):
    """
    Integrate from x0 down to x_end, returning (x_values, t_values, A).

    We use get_t_integrand_cosstep(...) for the integrand => continuous function
    that transitions from t1*x^ to t2*x^ each integer interval.
    """
    x_vals_desc = np.arange(x0, x_end - delta_x, -delta_x)
    n_points = len(x_vals_desc)

    # Evaluate t(x0) from the continuous function
    t_x0 = get_t_integrand_cosstep(x0, sigma, t1, t2, freq)
    A = - (2*t_x0*np.cos(p0))**2

    T_vals_desc = np.zeros(n_points)
    dx = delta_x

    for i in range(n_points-1):
        current_x = x_vals_desc[i]
        t_int = get_t_integrand_cosstep(current_x, sigma, t1, t2, freq)
        denom = np.sqrt((2*t_int)**2 + A)
        dt = dx / np.maximum(denom, 1e-12)
        T_vals_desc[i+1] = T_vals_desc[i] + dt

    T_vals_desc *= branch

    # reverse => ascending
    x_values = x_vals_desc[::-1]
    t_values = T_vals_desc[::-1]
    return x_values, t_values, A

def compute_integrated_t_asc(x_start, x_end, sigma, p0, t1, t2, freq=1.0, delta_x=1.0, branch=1):
    """
    Integrate from x_start up to x_end, returning (x_values, t_values, A).
    Also uses get_t_integrand_cosstep(...) for the integrand.
    """
    if x_start == 0:
        eps = delta_x
        x_eff = np.arange(eps, x_end+delta_x, delta_x)
        prepend_zero = True
    else:
        x_eff = np.arange(x_start, x_end+delta_x, delta_x)
        prepend_zero = False

    n_points = len(x_eff)
    t_x0 = get_t_integrand_cosstep(x_end, sigma, t1, t2, freq)
    A = - (2*t_x0*np.cos(p0))**2

    T_vals = np.zeros(n_points)
    dx = delta_x

    for i in range(n_points-1):
        current_x = x_eff[i]
        t_int = get_t_integrand_cosstep(current_x, sigma, t1, t2, freq)
        denom = np.sqrt((2*t_int)**2 + A)
        dt = dx/np.maximum(denom,1e-12)
        T_vals[i+1] = T_vals[i] + dt

    T_vals *= branch

    if prepend_zero:
        x_values = np.concatenate(([0], x_eff))
        T_vals = np.concatenate(([0], T_vals))
    else:
        x_values = x_eff

    return x_values, T_vals, A

import numpy as np

###############################################################################
#             COSINE-STEP FUNCTION: transitions between t1*x^ and t2*x^     #
###############################################################################
def raised_cosine_step(alpha, w):
    """
    Returns a smooth step function over alpha in [0,1).
    For alpha <= 0.5-w/2, output is 0; for alpha >= 0.5+w/2, output is 1;
    in between, a half-cosine ramp is used.
    """

    step_vals = np.zeros_like(alpha_arr)
    left  = 0.5 - w/2
    right = 0.5 + w/2
    mask0 = (alpha_arr <= left)
    mask1 = (alpha_arr >= right)
    mask_mid = ~(mask0 | mask1)
    s = (alpha_arr[mask_mid] - left) / (right - left)
    step_vals[mask_mid] = 0.5 * (1 - np.cos(np.pi * s))
    step_vals[mask1] = 1.0
    return step_vals

def get_t_integrand_cosstep(x, sigma, t1, t2, freq):
    """
    Continuous integrand function.
    For each x, let n = floor(x) and  = x - n.
      - If n is even, base = t1 and target = t2.
      - If n is odd,  base = t2 and target = t1.
    Then T(x) = x^ * [ base + (target - base)*step() ],
    where step() = raised_cosine_step(, w) with w = 1/freq.
    """
    x_arr = np.asarray(x, dtype=float)
    n = np.floor(x_arr).astype(int)
    alpha = x_arr - n
    parity = (n % 2 == 1)  # True if odd
    base = np.where(parity, t2, t1)
    targ = np.where(parity, t1, t2)
    w = 1.0 / freq
    frac = raised_cosine_step(alpha, w)
    amplitude = base + (targ - base) * frac
    return x_arr**sigma * amplitude

###############################################################################
#                 DISCRETE INTEGRAND FOR COMPARISON (t1/t2)                   #
###############################################################################
def get_t_integrand_discrete(x, sigma, t1, t2):
    """
    Discrete integrand: For x in [n, n+1),
      if n is even, return t1*x^; if n is odd, return t2*x^.
    """
    x_arr = np.asarray(x, dtype=float)
    n = np.floor(x_arr).astype(int)
    parity = (n % 2 == 1)
    base = np.where(parity, t2, t1)
    return (x_arr**sigma) * base

###############################################################################
#                           1) SSH CODE (UNCHANGED)                           #
###############################################################################
def build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma):
    """
    Build the SSH Hamiltonian on a 1D lattice of N sites.
    """
    H = np.zeros((N, N), dtype=complex)
    for i in range(N-1):
        v_i = v * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        w_i = w * ((i + 1) / (N-1))**sigma
        if i % 2 == 0:
            H[i, i+1] = -v_i
            H[i+1, i] = -v_i
        else:
            H[i, i+1] = -w_i
            H[i+1, i] = -w_i
    return H

def gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega):
    """
    Create a Gaussian wave packet.
    """
    n = np.arange(N)
    psi = np.exp(-0.5*((n - n0)/omega)**2) * np.exp(1j*p0*n)
    psi /= np.linalg.norm(psi)
    return psi

def run_time_evolution_ssh(N, v, w, sigma, n0, p0, omega, dt, T):
    """
    Evolve an initial Gaussian wave packet under the SSH Hamiltonian
    and return (rescaled_positions, rescaled_times).
    """
    H_SSH = build_ssh_hamiltonian(N, v, w, sigma)
    U = expm(-1j*H_SSH*dt)
    psi = gaussian_wave_packet(N, n0, p0, omega)
    t_steps = int(np.round(T / dt))
    psi_t = [np.abs(psi.copy())]
    for step in range(t_steps):
        psi = U @ psi
        psi_t.append(np.abs(psi))
    peak_positions = []
    rescaled_times = []
    rescaled_positions = []
    for step, psi_abs in enumerate(psi_t):
        peak_index = np.argmax(psi_abs)
        peak_positions.append(peak_index)
        t_val = step * dt
        rescaled_times.append(t_val / N)
        rescaled_positions.append(peak_index / N)
    return np.array(rescaled_positions), np.array(rescaled_times)

###############################################################################
#         2) NUMERICAL INTEGRATION OF CONTINUOUS & DISCRETE INTEGRANDS         #
###############################################################################
# For the forward integration (particle moves from x0 to 0):
def integrate_continuous_forward(x0, sigma, p0, t1, t2, freq, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    Compute the forward integration of the continuous integrand using Simpson's rule.
    Here we define a new variable u = x0 - x so that the integration is done
    on an ascending grid in u. Then:
         T_forward(x) = _{0}^{u} f(x0 - ) d,
    where u = x0 - x. This gives T_forward(x0) = 0 and T_forward(0) = I_total.
    """
    # Create ascending grid for u from 0 to x0.
    u_vals = np.arange(0, x0 + delta_x, delta_x)
    # Map back to x: x = x0 - u, so that when u = 0, x = x0; when u = x0, x = 0.
    x_vals = x0 - u_vals
    # Compute constant A using the continuous function at x0:
    T_x0 = get_t_integrand_cosstep(x0, sigma, t1, t2, freq)
    A = - (2 * T_x0 * np.cos(p0))**2
    # Evaluate the integrand f(x) = 1/sqrt((2*T_cont(x))^2 + A) on the grid x = x0 - u.
    f_vals = 1.0 / np.sqrt((2 * get_t_integrand_cosstep(x_vals, sigma, t1, t2, freq))**2 + A)
    # Compute cumulative integral as a function of u using Simpson's rule.
    cum = np.zeros_like(u_vals)
    for i in range(1, len(u_vals)):
        cum[i] = simpson(f_vals[:i+1], u_vals[:i+1])
    # T_forward(x) = cumulative integral, with T_forward(x0)=0 and T_forward(0)=I_total.
    T_forward = cum * branch
    # Note: x_vals is descending from x0 to 0.
    return x_vals, T_forward, A

# For the backward integration (particle bounces from wall at x=0 back to x0):
def integrate_continuous_backward(x0, sigma, p0, t1, t2, freq, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    Compute the backward integration of the continuous integrand (from x=0 to x0)
    using Simpson's rule. Here the integration is done on an ascending x-grid.
    We define:
         T_backward(x) = I_total + _{0}^{x} f(x') dx',
    where I_total = _{0}^{x0} f(x') dx'. Thus T_backward(0)=I_total and T_backward(x0)=2I_total.
    """
    x_vals = np.arange(0, x0 + delta_x, delta_x)
    T_x0 = get_t_integrand_cosstep(x0, sigma, t1, t2, freq)
    A = - (2 * T_x0 * np.cos(p0))**2
    f_vals = 1.0 / np.sqrt((2 * get_t_integrand_cosstep(x_vals, sigma, t1, t2, freq))**2 + A)
    cum = np.zeros_like(x_vals)
    for i in range(1, len(x_vals)):
        cum[i] = simpson(f_vals[:i+1], x_vals[:i+1])
    I_total = cum[-1]
    T_backward = (I_total + cum) * branch
    return x_vals, T_backward, A

# For discrete integrand integration, we use a simple Riemann sum.
def integrate_discrete_forward(x0, sigma, p0, t1, t2, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    Compute the forward integration of the discrete integrand via Riemann summation.
    Using variable u = x0 - x, with x = x0 - u.
    """
    u_vals = np.arange(0, x0 + delta_x, delta_x)
    x_vals = x0 - u_vals
    T_x0_disc = get_t_integrand_discrete(x0, sigma, t1, t2)
    A = - (2 * T_x0_disc * np.cos(p0))**2
    f_vals = 1.0 / np.sqrt((2 * get_t_integrand_discrete(x_vals, sigma, t1, t2))**2 + A)
    cum = np.zeros_like(u_vals)
    for i in range(1, len(u_vals)):
        cum[i] = cum[i-1] + delta_x * f_vals[i]
    T_forward_disc = cum * branch
    return x_vals, T_forward_disc, A

def integrate_discrete_backward(x0, sigma, p0, t1, t2, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    Compute the backward integration of the discrete integrand from x=0 to x0.
    """
    x_vals = np.arange(0, x0 + delta_x, delta_x)
    T_x0_disc = get_t_integrand_discrete(x0, sigma, t1, t2)
    A = - (2 * T_x0_disc * np.cos(p0))**2
    f_vals = 1.0 / np.sqrt((2 * get_t_integrand_discrete(x_vals, sigma, t1, t2))**2 + A)
    cum = np.zeros_like(x_vals)
    for i in range(1, len(x_vals)):
        cum[i] = cum[i-1] + delta_x * f_vals[i]
    I_total = cum[-1]
    T_backward_disc = (I_total + cum) * branch
    return x_vals, T_backward_disc, A

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.linalg import expm
from scipy.integrate import simpson
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

###############################################################################
#             COSINE-STEP FUNCTION: transitions between t1*x^ and t2*x^     #
###############################################################################
def raised_cosine_step(alpha, w):
    """
    Returns a smooth step function over alpha in [0,1):
      - 0 for alpha <= 0.5 - w/2,
      - 1 for alpha >= 0.5 + w/2,
      - In between, a half-cosine ramp.
    """
    alpha_arr = np.asarray(alpha, dtype=float)
    step_vals = np.zeros_like(alpha_arr)
    left  = 0.5 - w/2
    right = 0.5 + w/2
    mask0 = (alpha_arr <= left)
    mask1 = (alpha_arr >= right)
    mask_mid = ~(mask0 | mask1)
    s = (alpha_arr[mask_mid] - left) / (right - left)
    step_vals[mask_mid] = 0.5 * (1 - np.cos(np.pi * s))
    step_vals[mask1] = 1.0
    return step_vals

def get_t_integrand_cosstep(x, sigma, t1, t2, freq):
    """
    Continuous integrand function.
    For each x, let n = floor(x) and  = x - n.
      - If n is even: base = t1, target = t2.
      - If n is odd:  base = t2, target = t1.
    Then, the integrand is given by:
         T_cont(x) = x^ * [ base + (target - base)*raised_cosine_step(, 1/freq) ].
    """
    x_arr = np.asarray(x, dtype=float)
    n = np.floor(x_arr).astype(int)
    alpha = x_arr - n
    parity = (n % 2 == 1)  # True if odd
    base = np.where(parity, t2, t1)
    targ = np.where(parity, t1, t2)
    w = 1.0 / freq
    frac = raised_cosine_step(alpha, w)
    amplitude = base + (targ - base) * frac
    return x_arr**sigma * amplitude

###############################################################################
#                 DISCRETE INTEGRAND FOR COMPARISON (t1/t2)                   #
###############################################################################
def get_t_integrand_discrete(x, sigma, t1, t2):
    """
    Discrete integrand:
      For x in [n, n+1), if n is even return t1*x^; if n is odd, return t2*x^.
    """
    x_arr = np.asarray(x, dtype=float)
    n = np.floor(x_arr).astype(int)
    parity = (n % 2 == 1)
    base = np.where(parity, t2, t1)
    return (x_arr**sigma) * base

###############################################################################
#      2) NUMERICAL INTEGRATION OF CONTINUOUS & DISCRETE INTEGRANDS (FOR KCC)   #
###############################################################################
# These functions represent the "KCC brute-force" integration method.
# They use a simple fixed-step summation (with an even/odd condition) for the discrete integrand.

def compute_integrated_t_KCC(x0, x_end, sigma, p0, t1, t2, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    KCC Brute-force forward integration from x0 down to x_end.
    Here the integrand is defined discretely:
       if index is even: use t1*x^,
       if odd:           use t2*x^.
    """
    x_vals_desc = np.arange(x0, x_end - delta_x, -delta_x)
    n_points = len(x_vals_desc)
    t_x0 = t1 * (x0**sigma)
    A = - (2 * t_x0 * np.cos(p0))**2
    T_vals_desc = np.zeros(n_points)
    dx = delta_x
    for i in range(n_points-1):
        # Use even/odd condition directly:
        if i % 2 == 0:
            t_int = t1 * (x_vals_desc[i]**sigma)
        else:
            t_int = t2 * (x_vals_desc[i]**sigma)
        denom = np.sqrt((2*t_int)**2 + A)
        dt = dx / np.maximum(denom, 1e-12)
        T_vals_desc[i+1] = T_vals_desc[i] + dt
    T_vals_desc *= branch
    x_values = x_vals_desc[::-1]   # reverse to ascending order
    t_values = T_vals_desc[::-1]
    return x_values, t_values, A

def compute_integrated_t_asc_KCC(x_start, x_end, sigma, p0, t1, t2, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    KCC Brute-force backward integration from x_start up to x_end.
    This computes the cumulative sum using the discrete integrand and then adds an offset.
    """
    if x_start == 0:
        eps = delta_x
        x_vals_eff = np.arange(eps, x_end + delta_x, delta_x)
        prepend_zero = True
    else:
        x_vals_eff = np.arange(x_start, x_end + delta_x, delta_x)
        prepend_zero = False
    n_points = len(x_vals_eff)
    t_x0 = t1 * (x_end**sigma)
    A = - (2 * t_x0 * np.cos(p0))**2
    T_vals = np.zeros(n_points)
    dx = delta_x
    for i in range(n_points-1):
        if i % 2 == 0:
            t_int = t1 * (x_vals_eff[i]**sigma)
        else:
            t_int = t2 * (x_vals_eff[i]**sigma)
        denom = np.sqrt((2*t_int)**2 + A)
        dt = dx / np.maximum(denom, 1e-12)
        T_vals[i+1] = T_vals[i] + dt
    T_vals *= branch
    if prepend_zero:
        x_values = np.concatenate(([0], x_vals_eff))
        T_vals = np.concatenate(([0], T_vals))
    else:
        x_values = x_vals_eff
    return x_values, T_vals, A

###############################################################################
#       3) NUMERICAL INTEGRATION OF CONTINUOUS & DISCRETE INTEGRANDS (SIMPSON)  #
###############################################################################
def integrate_continuous_forward(x0, sigma, p0, t1, t2, freq, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    Continuous forward integration using Simpson's rule.
    We use u = x0 - x so that the integration is done on an ascending grid in u.
    Then, T_forward(x) = _{0}^{u} f(x0 - )d, with u = x0 - x.
    This yields T_forward(x0)=0 and T_forward(0)=I_total.
    """
    u_vals = np.arange(0, x0 + delta_x, delta_x)
    x_vals = x0 - u_vals  # descending from x0 to 0
    T_x0 = get_t_integrand_cosstep(x0, sigma, t1, t2, freq)
    A = - (2 * T_x0 * np.cos(p0))**2
    f_vals = 1.0 / np.sqrt((2 * get_t_integrand_cosstep(x_vals, sigma, t1, t2, freq))**2 + A)
    cum = np.zeros_like(u_vals)
    for i in range(1, len(u_vals)):
        cum[i] = simpson(f_vals[:i+1], u_vals[:i+1])
    T_forward = cum * branch
    return x_vals, T_forward, A

def integrate_continuous_backward(x0, sigma, p0, t1, t2, freq, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    Continuous backward integration using Simpson's rule on an ascending x-grid.
    Define T_backward(x) = I_total + _{0}^{x} f(x') dx',
    where I_total = _{0}^{x0} f(x') dx'. Then T_backward(0)=I_total and T_backward(x0)=2I_total.
    """
    x_vals = np.arange(0, x0 + delta_x, delta_x)
    T_x0 = get_t_integrand_cosstep(x0, sigma, t1, t2, freq)
    A = - (2 * T_x0 * np.cos(p0))**2
    f_vals = 1.0 / np.sqrt((2 * get_t_integrand_cosstep(x_vals, sigma, t1, t2, freq))**2 + A)
    cum = np.zeros_like(x_vals)
    for i in range(1, len(x_vals)):
        cum[i] = simpson(f_vals[:i+1], x_vals[:i+1])
    I_total = cum[-1]
    T_backward = (I_total + cum) * branch
    return x_vals, T_backward, A

def integrate_discrete_forward(x0, sigma, p0, t1, t2, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    Discrete forward integration using a brute-force Riemann sum.
    Define u = x0 - x so that when u=0, x=x0; when u=x0, x=0.
    """
    u_vals = np.arange(0, x0 + delta_x, delta_x)
    x_vals = x0 - u_vals
    T_x0_disc = get_t_integrand_discrete(x0, sigma, t1, t2)
    A = - (2 * T_x0_disc * np.cos(p0))**2
    f_vals = 1.0 / np.sqrt((2 * get_t_integrand_discrete(x_vals, sigma, t1, t2))**2 + A)
    cum = np.zeros_like(u_vals)
    for i in range(1, len(u_vals)):
        cum[i] = cum[i-1] + delta_x * f_vals[i]
    T_forward_disc = cum * branch
    return x_vals, T_forward_disc, A

def integrate_discrete_backward(x0, sigma, p0, t1, t2, delta_x=1e-5, branch=1):
    """
    Discrete backward integration using a brute-force Riemann sum on an ascending grid.
    Define T_backward(x) = I_total + _{0}^{x} f(x')dx', where I_total is the total forward sum.
    """
    x_vals = np.arange(0, x0 + delta_x, delta_x)
    T_x0_disc = get_t_integrand_discrete(x0, sigma, t1, t2)
    A = - (2 * T_x0_disc * np.cos(p0))**2
    f_vals = 1.0 / np.sqrt((2 * get_t_integrand_discrete(x_vals, sigma, t1, t2))**2 + A)
    cum = np.zeros_like(x_vals)
    for i in range(1, len(x_vals)):
        cum[i] = cum[i-1] + delta_x * f_vals[i]
    I_total = cum[-1]
    T_backward_disc = (I_total + cum) * branch
    return x_vals, T_backward_disc, A

###############################################################################
#                           4) MAIN COMBINED EXAMPLE                          #
###############################################################################
def main_combined():
    # -------------------- Part A: SSH Wave-Packet Evolution --------------------
    N = 1000
    v = 1
    w = 2
    sigma_ssh = 0.5
    n0 = 800
    p0_ssh = -np.pi/2
    omega = 9
    dt = 0.1
    T = 2000
    ssh_positions, ssh_times = run_time_evolution_ssh(N, v, w, sigma_ssh, n0, p0_ssh, omega, dt, T)

    # -------------------- Part B: Integration of Integrands --------------------
    # Set x0_val as the starting position (0.8) at time 0.
    x0_val = 0.8
    t1_val = v
    t2_val = w
    sigma_bf = sigma_ssh
    p0_bf = -np.pi/2
    freq_val = 20  # Adjust frequency: larger freq -> more step-like
    delta_x = 1e-5
    branch = 1

    # (i) Continuous Integration using Simpson's rule:
    x_forward_cont, T_forward_cont, A_cont = integrate_continuous_forward(x0_val, sigma_bf, p0_bf, t1_val, t2_val, freq_val, delta_x, branch)
    x_backward_cont, T_backward_cont, _ = integrate_continuous_backward(x0_val, sigma_bf, p0_bf, t1_val, t2_val, freq_val, delta_x, branch)
    # Offset backward integration by the total forward time:
    I_total_cont = T_forward_cont[ -1]  # note: forward integration: last value corresponds to x=0
    T_backward_cont += I_total_cont

    # (ii) Discrete Integration using Riemann summation:
    x_forward_disc, T_forward_disc, A_disc = integrate_discrete_forward(x0_val, sigma_bf, p0_bf, t1_val, t2_val, delta_x, branch)
    x_backward_disc, T_backward_disc, _ = integrate_discrete_backward(x0_val, sigma_bf, p0_bf, t1_val, t2_val, delta_x, branch)
    I_total_disc = T_forward_disc[-1]
    T_backward_disc += I_total_disc

    # (iii) KCC Brute-Force Integration (using our original compute_integrated_t functions for discrete integrand)
    x_forward_KCC, T_forward_KCC, A_KCC = compute_integrated_t(x0_val, 0, sigma_bf, p0_bf, t1_val, t2_val, delta_x, branch)
    x_backward_KCC, T_backward_KCC, _ = compute_integrated_t_asc(0, x0_val, sigma_bf, p0_bf, t1_val, t2_val, delta_x, branch)
    I_total_KCC = T_forward_KCC[0]  # since these functions reverse order so that forward curve is ascending from 0 to x0
    T_backward_KCC += I_total_KCC

    # -------------------- Plot: All Four Curves --------------------
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    # SSH evolution:
    plt.plot(ssh_positions, ssh_times, 'o', ms=2, label="SSH wave-packet evolution")
    # Continuous integration (forward, from x0 to 0):
    plt.plot(x_forward_cont, T_forward_cont, '-', lw=2, label=f"Continuous Forward (Simpson, freq={freq_val})")
    # Continuous integration (backward, from 0 to x0):
    plt.plot(x_backward_cont, T_backward_cont, ':', lw=2, color='blue', label="Continuous Backward")
    # Discrete integration (forward):
    plt.plot(x_forward_disc, T_forward_disc, '--', lw=2, color='red', label="Discrete Forward (Riemann)")
    # Discrete integration (backward):
    plt.plot(x_backward_disc, T_backward_disc, '-.', lw=2, color='orange', label="Discrete Backward")
    # KCC brute-force integration (forward):
    plt.plot(x_forward_KCC, T_forward_KCC, '-', lw=2, color='magenta', label="KCC Forward")
    # KCC brute-force integration (backward):
    plt.plot(x_backward_KCC, T_backward_KCC, '--', lw=2, color='cyan', label="KCC Backward")
    plt.xlabel("x (rescaled)")
    plt.ylabel("Integrated t (rescaled)")
    plt.title(f"Comparison of SSH vs. Integrated Curves\nx0={x0_val}, (t1,t2)=({t1_val},{t2_val}), sigma={sigma_bf}, freq={freq_val}")
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.legend(fontsize='small')
    plt.show()

    # -------------------- Plot: Integrand Comparison --------------------
    x_compare = np.linspace(0, x0_val, 1000)
    T_conti = get_t_integrand_cosstep(x_compare, sigma_bf, t1_val, t2_val, freq_val)
    T_disc = get_t_integrand_discrete(x_compare, sigma_bf, t1_val, t2_val)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    plt.plot(x_compare, T_conti, lw=2, label="Continuous cos-step integrand")
    plt.plot(x_compare, T_disc, '--', lw=2, label="Discrete integrand")
    plt.title(f"Integrand Comparison: Continuous vs. Discrete\nfreq={freq_val}, (t1,t2)=({t1_val},{t2_val}), sigma={sigma_bf}")
    plt.xlabel("x")
    plt.ylabel("t(x)")
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main_combined()
